{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c8c465e2-cb36-46d8-8f4d-ef324120b4c8","content":"Your project is already set up with the HotReload package. Here's how to use it:\n\n**Run tests in hot-reload mode:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --hotreload\n```\n\nThis starts a watch session — when you save changes to `EmailValidatorTests.cs`, the tests automatically re-run without restarting.\n\n**Your current failures:** `IsValidEmail` only checks for non-empty strings but doesn't check for `@`. So `Validate_MissingAtSign_ReturnsFalse` will fail.\n\n**Workflow:**\n1. Start `dotnet test --hotreload` in one terminal\n2. Edit and save `EmailValidatorTests.cs` (fix `IsValidEmail`)\n3. Tests re-run instantly — no manual rebuild needed\n\nWant me to start the hot-reload session and fix the `IsValidEmail` method?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"96396f04-b879-49d0-b10a-5bd0aa1823b7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to use the HotReload extension to iterate on fixes. Let me explain how to use it.\n\nThe `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` package enables a \"watch mode\" for tests using `dotnet test --hotreload`. When running in this mode, the test runner watches for file changes and automatically re-runs tests when you save changes, similar to `dotnet watch` but specifically for tests.\n\nLet me check if I can demonstrate this. The project already has the package. The way to use it is:\n\n```\ndotnet test --hotreload\n```\n\nOr with the newer testing platform:\n\n\n```\ndotnet run -- --hotreload\n```\n\nLet me verify the correct command.","outputTokens":375,"requestId":"E3C8:1AA0D2:6B5B92:7B5297:6A052921"},"id":"082f2940-85d6-4f1a-909e-ae906484bd61","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:45:15.150Z","parentId":"84382028-7927-4214-a6c0-0a6b66110500"}
